            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this PEI tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool estimates your Prince Edward Island (PEI) provincial
                income tax and combined federal + provincial tax based on your
                annual taxable income, RRSP contributions, and basic
                non-refundable tax credits. It is designed for residents of PEI
                for tax purposes.
              </p>
              <p>
                The calculator uses current PEI and federal tax brackets and
                basic personal amounts for 2024–2025 (with 2025 figures
                projected from 2024 where necessary). It also estimates Canada
                Pension Plan (CPP) and Employment Insurance (EI) contributions
                for employment income.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Taxable income after RRSP</h3>
              <p>
                First we subtract your RRSP contributions from your gross
                taxable income:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Taxable income</strong> = max(0, Gross income − RRSP
                  contributions)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                This taxable income is used for both federal and PEI provincial
                tax calculations.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Applying PEI provincial tax brackets</h3>
              <p>
                PEI uses a progressive tax system with several income brackets.
                For each bracket, income within the range is taxed at that
                bracket’s rate. The calculator applies the PEI brackets for the
                selected year and sums the tax across brackets.
              </p>
              <p>In simplified form:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  Provincial tax = Σ (Income in bracket × PEI rate for that
                  bracket)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Federal income tax</h3>
              <p>
                Federal tax is calculated the same way, using the federal tax
                brackets for the selected year. The tool then subtracts the
                basic personal amount and any additional non-refundable credits
                you enter, multiplied by the lowest federal and PEI rates.
              </p>

              <h3>4. CPP and EI (optional)</h3>
              <p>
                If you choose “Estimate automatically” and your income type is
                employment, the calculator estimates:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  CPP contributions on pensionable earnings between the yearly
                  minimum and maximum.
                </li>
                <li>
                  EI premiums on insurable earnings up to the annual maximum.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                These are added to your total deductions so you can see a
                realistic net income figure.
              </p>

              <h3>5. Average and marginal tax rates</h3>
              <p>The calculator shows:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Average PEI tax rate</strong> = PEI tax ÷ gross
                  income.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Average total tax rate</strong> = (PEI + federal +
                  CPP/EI) ÷ gross income.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Marginal rates</strong> based on the bracket your last
                  dollar of income falls into for PEI and federal, and the
                  combined marginal rate.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>What this PEI tax calculator is useful for</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>Estimating your total tax bill as a PEI resident.</li>
                <li>Comparing job offers or salary changes.</li>
                <li>Planning RRSP contributions to reduce tax.</li>
                <li>
                  Checking whether your paycheque deductions look reasonable.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The results are estimates only and do not replace official
                calculations from the Canada Revenue Agency (CRA) or the PEI
                Department of Finance.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Assumes you are a resident of PEI for the entire tax year.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Does not handle complex situations (e.g., split income,
                  capital gains, stock options).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Uses combined “other credits” as a single dollar amount you
                  enter.
                </li>
                <li>
                  CPP/EI estimates assume a single full-year job with no other
                  payroll sources.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For detailed personal advice, consult a CPA or tax professional
                familiar with Canadian and PEI tax rules.
              </p>
            </section>

            <section class="prose mt-10" id="pei-tax-faq">
              <h2>PEI tax calculator – frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Does this calculator include PEI sales tax (HST)?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This tool focuses on <strong>income tax</strong> for Prince
                Edward Island residents. PEI uses the Harmonized Sales Tax (HST)
                on purchases, which combines federal GST and provincial sales
                tax. HST is not part of your income tax return and is not
                included here.
              </p>

              <h3>Which tax year should I choose?</h3>
              <p>
                Use the year that matches the income you are reporting. For
                example, if you are filing your 2024 return in spring 2025,
                choose 2024. If you are planning ahead for next year’s income,
                choose 2025 (estimate).
              </p>

              <h3>How accurate is this PEI tax calculator?</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator uses current published federal and PEI tax
                brackets and basic personal amounts, and standard CPP/EI rates
                and thresholds. However, your actual tax can differ due to
                additional credits, deductions, benefits, and specific CRA
                rules. Treat the result as a high-quality estimate, not an
                official assessment.
              </p>

              <h3>Can non-residents of PEI use this calculator?</h3>
              <p>
                You can use it for a rough idea of PEI tax on PEI-source income,
                but non-resident tax rules are more complex. If you are not a
                resident of PEI for tax purposes, consult CRA guidance or a tax
                professional.
              </p>
